    "answer_id" : 2559784,
    "question_id" : 2559759,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>The following Regex can be used to identify the capitals inside words:</p>\n\n<pre><code>\"((?&lt;=[a-z0-9])[A-Z]|(?&lt;=[a-zA-Z])[0-9]]|(?&lt;=[A-Z])[A-Z](?=[a-z]))\"\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>It matches every capital letter, that is ether after a non-capital letter or digit or followed by a lower case letter and every digit after a letter.</p>\n\n<p>How to insert a space before them is beyond my Java skills =)</p>\n\n<p><em>Edited to include the digit case and the PDF Loader case.</em></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 117099,
      "reputation" : 142,
      "user_id" : 306805,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0a2ab2d034cee21110cbfa389add56ae?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Felix",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/306805/felix"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1270119965,
    "creation_date" : 1270119965,
    "answer_id" : 2559894,
    "question_id" : 2559759,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>I think you will have to iterate over the string and detect changes from lowercase to uppercase, uppercase to lowercase, alphabetic to numeric, numeric to alphabetic. On every change you detect insert a space with one exception though: on a change from upper- to lowercase you insert the space one character before.</p>\n"
