    "question_id" : 2559759,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In my case, all letters of the resulting words must be upper-case if their length is 2. Inspired by <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/46945726/2358409\">this answer</a>, I solved my issue with the common method below.</p>\n<pre><code>/**\n * splits a pascal-case or camel-case string into individual words\n * \n * @param s the pascal-case or camel-case string to be splitted\n * @param lengthLimitAllUppercase resulting words whose length do not exceed this parameter, all letters are converted to upper-case\n */\npublic static String camelCaseToWords(String s, int lengthLimitAllUppercase) {\n    return Arrays.stream(StringUtils.splitByCharacterTypeCamelCase(s)) //\n            .map(w -&gt; w.length() &lt;= lengthLimitAllUppercase ? w.toUpperCase() : StringUtils.capitalize(w)) //\n            .collect(Collectors.joining(StringUtils.SPACE));\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>The <code>jUnit</code> test for my particular case looks as follows.</p>\n<pre><code>@Test\npublic void testCamelCaseToWords() {\n    assertEquals(&quot;OS Product Type&quot;, camelCaseToWords(&quot;osProductType&quot;, 2));\n    assertEquals(&quot;CS System Family&quot;, camelCaseToWords(&quot;csSystemFamily&quot;, 2));\n    assertEquals(&quot;Time Zone&quot;, camelCaseToWords(&quot;timeZone&quot;, 2));\n    assertEquals(&quot;OS Product Type&quot;, camelCaseToWords(&quot;OsProductType&quot;, 2));\n    assertEquals(&quot;CS System Family&quot;, camelCaseToWords(&quot;CsSystemFamily&quot;, 2));\n    assertEquals(&quot;Time Zone&quot;, camelCaseToWords(&quot;TimeZone&quot;, 2));\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
