    "last_activity_date" : 1719356143,
    "last_edit_date" : 1719356143,
    "creation_date" : 1719099882,
    "answer_id" : 78657445,
    "question_id" : 2559759,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This approach also works. As a developer, I distinguish camelCase from PascalCase - both are shown below, although the camel case version uses an underscore to keep it a valid XML name.</p>\n<pre><code>String name = &quot;camelCase&quot;;\nStringBuilder bldr = new StringBuilder();\nchar c;\nfor (int i=0; i&lt;name.length(); i++) {\n    c = name.charAt(i);\n    if (Character.isUpperCase(c)) {\n        bldr.append(&quot;_&quot;);\n        bldr.append(Character.toLowerCase(c));\n    } else {\n        bldr.append(c);\n    }\n}\nString answer = bldr.toString();//camel_case\n</code></pre>\n<p>or</p>\n<pre><code>String name = &quot;PascalCase&quot;;\nStringBuilder bldr = new StringBuilder();\nchar c;\nfor (int i=0; i&lt;name.length(); i++) {\n    c = name.charAt(i);\n    if (i &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; Character.isUpperCase(c)) {\n        bldr.append(&quot; &quot;);\n    }\n    bldr.append(c);\n}\nString answer = bldr.toString();//Pascal Case\n</code></pre>\n"
  } ],
